00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:46.130
So developers have been
working with Firebase

00:05:46.130 --> 00:05:49.220
with their Android apps and
their iOS apps and so forth.

00:05:49.220 --> 00:05:50.310
But this adds a new layer.

00:05:50.310 --> 00:05:53.440
This is like a back end
intelligence to real time data.

00:05:53.440 --> 00:05:55.921
DAVID EAST: Yeah, it's
funny talking about Firebase

00:05:55.921 --> 00:05:58.170
on the back end of things
because most people are used

00:05:58.170 --> 00:05:59.940
to using it on the front side.

00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:02.450
But what's cool about
that is not everything

00:06:02.450 --> 00:06:05.370
you can do from the phone,
because it's not always on,

00:06:05.370 --> 00:06:07.842
so you can't always be
routinely sending emails,

00:06:07.842 --> 00:06:10.050
or you can't send a push
notification from the phone.

00:06:10.050 --> 00:06:11.870
So those type of
things you can use

00:06:11.870 --> 00:06:15.560
Firebase for because you
spin it up on the server,

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:18.512
and it's not really like a
server, it's more of a client.

00:06:18.512 --> 00:06:20.470
So I built a ton of apps,
and this is something

00:06:20.470 --> 00:06:22.310
that I do quite frequently.

00:06:22.310 --> 00:06:26.400
And when you spin up this like
smart client that you can trust

00:06:26.400 --> 00:06:29.090
so you can put all of your keys
on there or your certificates,

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:30.506
and then that way,
it can send out

00:06:30.506 --> 00:06:32.670
push notifications and
response to something

00:06:32.670 --> 00:06:34.040
that happened in Firebase.

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:36.560
So now you have this client
that's sitting on a server,

00:06:36.560 --> 00:06:38.860
and you have your phone,
and they're totally away

00:06:38.860 --> 00:06:39.820
from each other.

00:06:39.820 --> 00:06:42.180
But yet, at the same time,
they're in total harmony,

00:06:42.180 --> 00:06:44.000
synchronizing the same data.

